mm: replace stale mmap_lock cacheline-placement comment

The comment above mmap_lock says its offset is "typically" 56 bytes
from the last cacheline boundary so that the rw_semaphore's 'count'
and 'owner' hot fields sit in two different cachelines, calls that
placement "very optimal", and warns against adding fields before
mmap_lock that would disturb it. That guidance is doubly stale:

1. The layout it describes no longer exists. Since commit
   8cea569ca785 ("sched/mmcid: Use proper data structures") inserted
   the cacheline-aligned mm_cid struct (and the sched_cache stats
   added another aligned block), mmap_lock sits 16 bytes past the
   last cacheline boundary on x86-64 defconfig-like builds: 'count'
   and 'owner' share one cacheline.

2. Re-measuring both layouts shows the described optimum has
   inverted, at least on this machine. On a Ryzen 9 7950X (32-thread
   VM, will-it-scale mmap1_threads -t 32, interleaved A/B alternating
   boots, 8 boots/side x 3 reps = n=24/side, Welch t-test), restoring
   the offset-56 split REGRESSES throughput by 1.7% (p=0.03) against
   today's offset-16 layout, and a full restoration that also
   separates the neighbouring fault-path fields regresses by 3.0%
   (p=0.001). Isolating mmap_lock on a fully dedicated cacheline
   performs identically to the current layout (-0.05%, p=0.94),
   which also shows the current co-tenants (pgtables_bytes,
   map_count, page_table_lock) cost nothing measurable on top of the
   line traffic the lock's own count updates already generate.

   A plausible explanation: on today's code every acquisition writes
   both 'count' and 'owner' (readers set owner via
   rwsem_set_reader_owned, writers store it on acquire), so splitting
   the two fields makes every acquire touch two cachelines, while the
   spinner traffic on 'owner' that the split was meant to isolate is
   OSQ-serialized to essentially one poller at a time (OSQ head, plus
   a handoff waiter). The split was established by commit
   2e3025434a6b ("mm: relocate 'write_protect_seq' in struct
   mm_struct") from a 2021 report (9.2% will-it-scale swing) whose
   bisected base predates the rwsem slowpath reworks in the years
   since (e.g. commit 617f3ef95177 ("locking/rwsem: Remove reader
   optimistic spinning") is not in the ancestry of the bisected
   commit), and the microarchitecture changed too (2021 Intel 0day
   vs. this Zen 4). The honest summary is that the optimum is at
   best uarch-dependent, not universal - which is enough to retire a
   comment that presents it as settled.

This is single-machine (Zen 4) data; if the split still helps on
other microarchitectures, that only reinforces the replacement
text's actual prescription: keep lock-free-hot fields off the line,
same-lock-writer fields are free, and re-measure before re-tuning.

Someone reading the current comment and "fixing" the offset back to
56 would regress the very benchmark the comment's lore comes from.

The wording being replaced was last touched by commit 61dc4358d37a
("mm: correct misleading comment on mmap_lock field in mm_struct"),
which converted the offset notation; the underlying guidance dates
to 2e3025434a6b.

No functional change.

Signed-off-by: David Vernet <void@manifault.com>

